  <h2 class="mt-14 mb-5">Vehicle Systems, Architecture &amp; Development</h2>

  <p class="mb-5 leading-relaxed">I've quite enjoyed working across the range of vehicles that we've been involved with. From supporting factory GT4 programmes running alongside F1 events, to UK TCR weekends at Snetterton. The variety matters.</p>

  <p class="mb-5 leading-relaxed">Moving between categories exposed me to a much broader set of problems than you typically see in a neatly scoped motorsport role.</p>

  <p class="mb-5 leading-relaxed">One moment that stands out was having to re-spec a battery after a series of 'random' errors which arose every time our car came to box. Battery voltage was OK, but after investigation we realised that the home-fligated battery was undersized and was dropping certain modules below voltage on engine start. Hence shutting a workable solution wasn't something I expected, but it pulled me deeper into electrical theory and systems than I had been before.</p>

  <p class="mb-5 leading-relaxed">This is also where my interest in electrical architecture and CAN systems really took hold. Learning how to add sensors to a loom, configure ECUs to receive and interpret those signals, and diagnose faults at a system level was unexpectedly engaging.</p>

  <p class="mb-10 leading-relaxed">Specifying the electrical architecture for a client-level, track-only hypercar currently in development has been something I've genuinely enjoyed; balancing modules and managing Baud rates across CAN buses has been a proper highlight.</p>

  <p class="mb-5 leading-relaxed">In practice, this work has involved:</p>
  <ul class="wd-list mb-10 space-y-2 leading-relaxed list-none">
    <li>Lap simulation and correlation</li>
    <li>Electrical systems and loom integration</li>
    <li>Electrical fault diagnoses (chasing grounds in abundance!)</li>
    <li>CAN architecture and management</li>
    <li>Racecar systems engineering using RaceCon, Sysma, M1</li>
  </ul>

